The black box in your car?
As American highway designers scramble to find money to fix a crumbling highway network, many are beginning to see a solution in a small black box that easily fits into your car's dashboard.
Devices that track every mile driven by a motorist and relay that information to law enforcement are at the heart of a controversial effort by Washington and the National Planning Administration to overhaul the outdated system of funding America's highways.
The usually fading design of the highways suddenly sparked intense debate and the creation of various associations.
Libertarians have been meeting with environmental groups and lobbying for the government to use these little boxes that would record your miles and maybe even where you're going and then use that information to compile a tax return.
The tea party is terrified.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also deeply concerned and has mentioned a number of privacy concerns.
And while Congress can't agree on whether to proceed, some states are waiting for nothing.
They're looking at how they can move to a system where the driver pays per mile of road they drive within the next decade.
Thousands of motorists have already taken their black boxes, some of which have GPS tracking, for testing.
This is a real necessity for our nation.
"This is not a matter of choosing too much", said Hasan Ikhrata, executive director of the Southern California Association of State Governments, which plans to start tracking the mileage of every California motorist by 2025.
It's going to change the way we pay these taxes.
That's what this technology is for.
The stimulus is the fact that the Highway Trust Fund funded by taxes Americans pay at gas stations is bottoming out.
Americans don't buy as much gas as they used to.
Cars will go a lot more miles per gallon.
The federal tax itself, 18.4 cents a gallon, hasn't increased in 20 years.
With gasoline so high, politicians are reluctant to raise taxes by even a single cent.
"A gasoline tax is simply not sustainable", said Lee Munnich, a transport policy expert at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently installed tracking devices in 500 cars to test this pay-per-mile system.
"In the long term, this seems to be the most logical alternative", he said.
Experts call it a mileage user fee.
Not surprisingly, this idea is popular with urban liberals, because taxes can be used to change driver behavior patterns, which can help reduce traffic congestion and greenhouse gas emissions, for example.
California planners look to this system to plan strategies to meet the goals set out in the ambitious global warming laws.
But Republican Bill Shuster, chairman of the Transportation Committee, said he also sees it as the most viable long-term alternative.
Free market advocates at the Reason Foundation also favor the idea of paying drivers for miles driven.
"It's not a tax that disappears into a black hole", said Adrian Moore, vice president of strategy at Reason.
People pay for what they get.
The initiative is also supported by two former U.S. transportation secretaries who in 2011 urged Congress to move toward pay-per-mile.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that was supposed to involve about 10,000 cars.
The House leadership, however, rejected the proposal, doing so because of concerns among rural lawmakers representing a segment of the population whose daily lives often involve traveling many miles to work outside the city.
However, a few states and cities are still moving forward on their own.
The most active is Oregon, which has conducted the largest experiment in the country involving 5,000 drivers.
These drivers will soon be paying the state mileage tax instead of the gas tax.
Nevada has already completed the pilot project.
New York is currently investigating the project.
Illinois is doing that to a limited extent with trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes 17 state departments of transportation, along with the east coast states (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida) is studying how they can implement this change.
But this concept has not only supporters.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer cars were recently equipped with the device, drivers were concerned about the government's ability to monitor their every move.
"Concerns about Big Brother-type surveillance and similar issues have been a big problem", said Alauddin Khan, who heads strategy and operations management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
It wasn't something people wanted.
As the pilot project proceeded, the American Civil Liberties Union of Nevada warned on its website: It would be very easy to turn these devices into full-fledged surveillance devices.
There is no need to build a huge, cumbersome technological infrastructure that will inevitably extend to recording the daily comings and goings of individuals.
Nevada is one of the few states that is trying to find available technology that would allow the state to track how many miles a car drives, but not exactly when and where.
If you can do that, Khan said, the public will be calmer.
The hunt for such technology has led some government agencies to a small company in California called True Mileage.
This company was not originally involved in the government's tax relief effort.
It wanted to break into the emerging market for liability insurance, where drivers would pay based on how much they drove.
But the device they are testing has caught the attention of road network designers because it does not use GPS and provides only a limited amount of information that is regularly recorded by a modem.
"People will be more willing to go if you don't track their speed and their location", says Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
Some of these pilot programmes have shown a number of major errors.
There are much cheaper and less intrusive ways to do this.
In Oregon, designers are experimenting with giving drivers a choice.
They can choose a GPS-enabled device or a non-GPS device.
Or they may not need to take any equipment and instead choose to pay a flat-rate fee based on the average mileage of all the residents of the state.
Elsewhere, they hope that a cautious public will embrace the concept as the device does more, not less.
In New York City, transit officials are working to develop a taxing system that would be equipped to pay additional parking fees, provide insurance based on miles driven, and collect speed data from other drivers so that motorists can avoid traffic jams.
Motorists will be willing to get involved because of the value of the benefits offered, says the city's projection document.
Some transportation designers, however, wonder if all the talk about paying per mile is just a giant sub-problem.
Officials at the San Francisco Bay Area Metropolitan Transportation Commission say Congress could very easily solve the problem of the bankrupt Highway Trust Fund by raising the gasoline tax.
A one-off or annual tax could be imposed on drivers of hybrid or other vehicles that do not use much fuel, so that they pay a fair share.
"No radical surgery is needed if you take a lot of aspirin", said Randy Rentschler, chairman of the Committee on Legislation and Public Affairs.
