George Kerevan: A divided Europe gives the Scots a choice
Another day, another scary story of independence.
This time, there is a warning that an independent Scotland's EU membership would be conditional on it joining Schengen.
This has given rise to stories of passport controls at Berwick and barbed wire along Hadrian's Wall.
The truth is that the Strathclyde newspapers mentioned the possible economic benefits of free movement with the rest of Europe, but  as you might expect  it didn't make the headlines.
Nor did anyone mention that EU Member States spend a lot of time adapting their official laws where it suits them.
Since Scotland is now out of Schengen, an offer of continued non-compliance would be a cheap concession for Brussels in exchange for whatever it really wants from the Scots.
So it's a pretty weak story.
And so old that it became a dig, a journalistic duck, that "independence means passport control", I heard at least 40 years ago.
Yet, there is an interesting point in this bearded storyteller.
Why should an independent Scotland be expected to listen to Europe at all?
Why trade the London chamout for the Brussels one, especially now?
This is the true story of Europe: the great post-war plan to unite Europe finally failed.
The euro crisis has officially put the so-called Europe project to rest.
Throughout Europe, parties dedicated to resisting the EU or abolishing the euro as a common currency are gaining influence.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party  founded this year  came out of nowhere and already won almost five million votes in the September federal elections, effectively "sweeping" the Free Democrats (the British equivalent of the Liberal Democrats) out of the Bundestag.
At home, there has always been opposition to the plan to create a federal Europe.
The current economic crisis, however, has become a defining moment.
The austerity imposed by Germany and the European Central Bank, coupled with the tightness of national economies through a single currency, have led many to believe that the Europe project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments managing high budget deficits  this was true only in the case of Greece.
Rather, it is a euro system that locks its members into exchange rates favourable to German exporters  and that is what German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of devaluing the domestic currency, Southern Europe is at a disadvantage in terms of domestic production compared to Germany.
The only solution is to cut public revenue and expenditure  as Germany encourages.
Behind the current budgetary and currency problems lies a deeper cause of Europe's poor performance.
As a result of the Green energy policy supported by Brussels  the code of conduct for supporting French and German firms at consumer expense , European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for petrol as it does in the United States.
This is a crippling cost disadvantage, as we have already seen in the case of Grangemouth.
All the wage freezes in the world wouldn't stop the European petrochemical industry from being trampled on by cheap shale oil from the US.
The result is a smoldering revolt, especially in France, once a zealous supporter of the EU.
After the war, the political elite in France saw the EU as a tool to keep Germany in check and allow Paris to rise to the level of Washington in the world.
Berlin, however, no longer needed Paris as a proof of political legitimacy and imposed its own economic policies in Europe, leaving the worn-out French economy to its fate.
The result: Marine Le Pen's right-wing, the anti-European National Front, has just won a crucial by-election, pushing the ruling Socialists to third place.
The Front is now the most popular party in France with 24% of the vote  a timely warning to British Labour that they cannot assume that a split on the right will automatically be positive on the left.
How is Le Pen handling her newfound popularity among white working class?
It would like to use the European elections next year to create an anti-European bloc across the European Parliament that is working against the single currency.
If the anti-European parties do well in this election, which they are likely to do, such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament for the first time in history.
I think that in the foreseeable future, growing anti-European sentiment and anti-monetary attitudes will merge and the euro will die.
The EU will not disappear, but rather become something freer in the sense of the "Europe of (sovereign) nations" that General de Gaulle favoured.
Germany and some of its satellite economies may keep the euro, but France and southern Europe will restore their own currencies.
I expect the UK to distance itself from this project and join the US.
But Washington's increased interest in the Pacific suggests Britain will be left to the Atlantic cold.
And where will Scotland be?
We can choose to be a part of (basically) Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests, including the ability to tell Berlin and Brussels when to leave us alone.
I suppose Scotland would do well in a loose arrangement of Europe, provided it kept its own currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries would be easier in a non-federal Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should follow Norway's example and maintain our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is  surprisingly  the most successful non-austerity political movement in Europe, winning a large majority in 2011 thanks to the opposition stance to the cuts planned (and implemented) by Labour Chancellor Alistair Darling and the subsequent coalition of Conservatives and Liberal Democrats.
It would be ridiculous if Scotland now voted for independence just to accept austerity measures dictated by Berlin and Brussels.
Early puberty: Early adulthood
Research has shown that African-American and Hispanic women reach puberty earlier than their white counterparts.
Physical changes do not mean that puberty is approaching
There's no evidence of hormones or other chemicals
Experts say that one of the triggers for early puberty may be the obesity epidemic.
The trend toward earlier puberty is not as apparent in boys.
Former CNN anchor Pat Etheridge is a journalist who specializes in children's health and family issues.
Should a mother be terrified when her daughter starts to grow breasts and pubic hair at age seven or eight?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these physical changes are fairly common among American girls and are the new standard.
"I spent a lot of time reassuring my parents that it's not usually a sign of rapid progress toward full puberty", said Kaplowitz.
Visible developmental signs, such as breast growth, pubic and forearm hair, and body odor, appear earlier in girls.
However, in the past 40 years, there has been little change in the age of first menstruation.
In the United States, the average age is now 12.5 years, down from 12.75 years in 1970.
"Once the breasts start to develop, it will be at least two to three years before the first menstrual period", says Kaplowitz, who is also the author of the book Early puberty in girls: The Essential Guide to Coping with This Common Problem.
The most reliable test of how puberty will progress is time.
There is debate about what activates the actual onset of puberty, but if breast growth is accompanied by a growth spurt before age 8, the girl is considered "premature".
In most cases, the process slows or stops  which can be closely monitored by paediatricians.
Rapid growth may be a reason for an endocrinologist to run tests to rule out serious problems, such as a tumor or cyst.
There are treatments that delay early menstruation and prevent another consequence: premature bone aging, which can eventually lead to stunting and shrinkage in adulthood.
Recommendations for medication and hormone therapy depend on the child's age, developmental rate, growth rate, and emotional maturity.
The psychosocial aspects are also important.
As for the use of medication, Kaplowitz is cautious, but he acknowledges that "repressing puberty can alleviate a girl's behavioral problems and her feelings of being different from her peers".
Another big problem is understandable: Parents simply do not want their very young daughters to have menstruation.
"They're worried she might get pregnant or how she'll handle her hygiene", Kaplowitz said.
"It was a shock", recalls one woman whose daughter started menstruating at age 10.
Even though there were signs and we talked about menstruation, she wasn't emotionally ready.
She came home from school scared and angry because she was the first of her friends.
There are many well-known theories about the causes of premature puberty.
But there is still no coherent evidence to blame hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media.
Boys, like girls, reach puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz suggests that the most serious cause is the obesity epidemic.
In 2001, he helped conduct a study on girls ages 6 to 9 that linked body fat to puberty timing.
Other findings support this conclusion, but there are many other contributing factors.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic women tend to reach puberty earlier than their white counterparts.
There are different explanations.
Globally, early puberty patterns seem to be influenced by everything from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another conundrum: Although boys develop facial hair and pubic hair at an early age, the trend toward full-blown early puberty is not as pronounced as it is for girls.
Other doctors attending the American Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) conference added to the complexity of the subject.
Acne and pubic hair are common, even in infants and toddlers.
"We have to be careful about how we identify the real onset of puberty", said Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Goryeo Children's Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to seek guidance from their pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
"It may mean having to talk to your child sooner than you expect", advises Kaplowitz.
If you remain calm, your child will likely respond well.
Girls who develop earlier need reassurance that even if it happens prematurely, it is a normal part of life.
