Aircraft manufacturers are fighting over seat width, big contracts at stake
A dispute over the width of second-class seats on long-haul flights between leading aircraft manufacturers sparked a bitter exchange of views at the Dubai Airshow this month.
The dispute concerns the width of the seats provided for long-haul economy class flights  not exactly the width that airlines would normally avoid, but whose space allocation is key to the efficiency claims of the latest aircraft offered by Airbus SAS and Boeing.
Airbus this week called for industry standards to offer at least 18 inches wide economy seats, but major U.S. rival Boeing says it's up to airlines to decide.
The dispute arose as aircraft manufacturers compete to sell the largest version of their twin-engine long-haul aircraft, with a potential record number of orders expected during the event from 17 to 21 November.
The way the rear of the aircraft is arranged  especially whether it has 9 or 10 seats side by side  is the basis of the economic performance requirements for the designs of new mini-jumbo aircraft.
Boeing says the upgraded 777X will carry 406 people in economy seats more than 17 inches wide, spread out over 10 in each row.
Airbus says that the competing version of its A350 model carries 350 people in 46 cm wide economy seats spread over nine.
Giant airplanes often compete with each other on technical issues through advertising in professional media.
Airbus is now appealing directly to the public ahead of the Dubai Airshow, where the 777X is expected to dominate with more than 100 orders.
He recently gave a preview of what could be the start of a new advertising war by showing a photograph of three people crammed into a restaurant to financiers with the caption "Would you like this?"
"Boeing promotes long-haul flights in seats narrower than those on regional turboprops", said Airbus sales manager John Leahy.
As diets change, people get bigger, but the seats on planes haven't changed radically.
Since the early 1970's, when the Boeing 747 jumbo defined modern long-haul air travel, by the turn of the century, the average American between the ages of 40 and 49 had increased in weight by 10 percent, according to the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services.
According to the U.S. Census Bureau, the average American in the 21st century has a waistline of 100 centimeters.
Airbus claims that its rival is sticking to a 1950s seat concept, when the average width of a newly christened aircraft was lower.
Airbus claims to have conducted research that suggests that extending the seat by an inch [2.5 cm] improves sleep quality by 53 percent.
Boeing rejects Airbus' seat sizes, saying it is not in the airplane manufacturers' power to decide how airlines export fees and equipment.
The company also says that research shows that the cabin experience depends on more than just seat width.
It's really about giving airlines flexibility and enabling them to do the things they believe they need to do to be successful, said cabin space expert Kent Craver.
They don't want us to dictate what's profitable.
They know their business better than anyone.
For passengers, more elbow room is essential, but for suppliers, it is a growing problem that can affect revenues.
Behind this dispute is a race for aircraft orders with estimated sales of at least $700 billion in catalogue prices over the next few decades, enough to tip the balance of American and European exports.
As Reuters reported in July, the seating arrangement is exactly what drives the battle between the last planes.
Both Airbus and Boeing claim that their latest twin-engine long-haul designs are 20 per cent more efficient than the market leader in this segment, the 365-seat Boeing 777-300ER.
Boeing's performance requirements depend in part on a comparison of the design of the 10 seat 777X with the 9 seat 777 concept.
The unit cost profit is weakened compared to the 10-seater concept.
"The reason Boeing is doing this is to fill more seats and make its planes more competitive with our products", said Kevin Keniston, head of passenger comfort at Airbus for Europe.
On the other hand, analysts say that the 10-seat cabins in a row for existing 777 models are in line with the fact that many passengers are for a denser layout, which can go hand in hand with lower fares.
"A seat that is 45 centimeters wide would be great for passengers, but the reality is that from an Airbus business perspective, the design is motivated by the threat of the 777", said cabin interior expert Mary Kirby, founder and editor of Runway Girl Network.
Airbus and Boeing do not supply seats, but they offer the airlines a catalogue of suppliers to choose from.
Travelers even carry a measuring tape to check competing arrangements.
While boasting of comfort, all manufacturers also offer high density aircraft for low-cost airlines and regional travellers.
Airbus is offering an A350 with 10 rows of seats, but says it hasn't sold it yet.
Until recently, Airbus emphasized the need for more cabin adjustments by offering wider aisle seats on some of its aircraft.
Experts say that without the support of a single other large modern aircraft manufacturer, the call for new industry standards will go unheeded, but may deter a surge in 777X sales.
