A new nicotine vaccine may take away the pleasure of smoking
Scientists have developed a vaccine against nicotine that can take away the pleasure of smoking a cigarette.
A single dose of the vaccine was able to protect a mouse from nicotine addiction for life.
Before human trials, further tests will take several years, but Professor Ronald Crystal of Weill Cornell Medical College in New York says the first signs are good.
"We hope this kind of vaccination strategy can finally help the millions of smokers who have tried to quit and exhausted all the methods available on the market today, but have found that their nicotine addiction is too strong to overcome all current approaches", said Professor Cornell.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been engineered to carry the genetic information to make anti-nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects liver cells, which then start to produce a steady stream of these antibodies.
Antibodies hunt down all the nicotine molecules in the bloodstream and neutralize them before they reach the brain, preventing the smoker from getting nicotine poisoning.
In the tests, the vaccinated mice that were supplemented with nicotine continued their normal activities.
But the mice that weren't vaccinated calmed down, the researchers said, which is a sign that nicotine had gotten into their brains.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
Injections had to be given so often to maintain sufficient antibody levels, so they proved expensive and impractical.
The cost of a new vaccine should be much lower because it turns liver cells into factories to make antibodies.
Professor Crystal said that if future vaccines were completely safe for humans, they could be given to children before they even get a cigarette taste, thus preventing nicotine addiction.
However, smokers are much more likely to use it to quit.
"They will know that if they start smoking again, the nicotine vaccine will not give them any pleasure, and that will help them quit", he said.
British scientists said the results were interesting, but they cautioned that more research was needed.
