Although she earns $2,400 a month as an administrator and her husband also works, the family's monthly income is insufficient, she says.
Demand across Southeast Asia  where household debt is rising  is indeed such that ValueMax, where the woman is transacting, became the third-highest-rated mortgage company on the Singapore stock exchange this week.
Stopping jewellery is not only a quick way to borrow 1,300 SGD in the case of Mrs. Amirthalinga , but it is also almost as cheap as an unsecured bank loan.
The Singaporean landlords normally charge an annual interest rate of 17 percent, just above the 15.4 percent rate offered by United Overseas Bank, a local bank with a branch in the same shopping mall.
However, the advantages of the guarantee schemes are that they do not require any personal verification (payment history) or proof of income and can grant a loan faster than banks.
And so, with families feeling the pressure of rising living costs and rising household and consumer debt, millions of people across the region are turning to mortgages.
After five years of massive growth since the global financial crisis and cheap credit backed by loose monetary policy in advanced economies, low- and middle-income families are turning to mortgages to cope with their deteriorating financial situation.
This week, Standard & Poor's cited rising household credit usage, mainly due to rising rents, as a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
