Syria has destroyed vital chemical weapons production facilities and poison gas munitions, the Global Monitoring Committee on Chemical Weapons said on Thursday, as fierce fighting erupted in the north of the country near one of the sites where the toxic substances are believed to be stored.
On Thursday, a Syrian activist group said more than 120,000 civilians had been killed since the civil war began nearly three years ago.
The announcement from the Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons came the day before November 1st,
the deadline set by that organisation, based in The Hague, for Damascus to destroy or render inoperable all chemical weapons production facilities and machinery for mixing chemical substances to produce poison gas and to refill munitions.
The completion of this basically initial phase of destruction is a significant milestone in the ambitious timetable to destroy all of Damascus' chemical weapons by mid-2014.
Destroying the equipment means Syria will no longer be able to produce new chemical weapons.
However, Damascus has yet to begin the destruction of existing weapons and supplies.
It is estimated that this country has about 1,000 tons of chemical and weapons including yperite and sarin nerve gas.
The announcement came as fighting raged Thursday in the town of Safira, which experts say is home to a chemical weapons factory and a storage facility, the Britain-based Syrian Observatory for Human Rights said.
