FAA: Air travellers can now use technology on planes (but not call from their mobile phones)
Airline passengers will be able to use their electronic devices  door-to-door  in addition to calling from their mobile phones  to read, play games, watch movies and listen to music under eagerly awaited new rules issued by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) on Thursday.
But travelers should not expect changes to occur immediately.
How quickly the change will be implemented will vary by airline, FAA Administrator Michael Huerta said at a press conference.
Airlines will have to demonstrate to the FAA the extent to which their aircraft comply with the new rules and that they have updated the flight crew training manuals and equipment storage guidelines to comply with the new rules.
The FAA stated that it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices in aircraft.
Among the companies that have already submitted plans are Delta and JetBlue.
Depending on the status of such a plan, we can improve the widespread use of electronic devices very quickly, the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers are required to turn off their smartphones, tablets and other devices as soon as the doors of the aircraft are closed.
They can't turn them on until the plane reaches an altitude of 2 miles and the captain gives the go-ahead.
Passengers are expected to turn off their devices again when the aircraft descends to land and not to turn them on until the aircraft is on the ground.
Under the new rules, airlines whose aircraft are properly protected against electronic interference can allow their passengers to use their devices during takeoff, landing and departure, the FAA said.
Most new commercial aircraft and other aircraft that have been modified to allow passengers to use Wi-Fi at higher altitudes are expected to meet these criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the Professional Stewardship Association, welcomed the changes.
Once the new rules are safely in place  and we will work closely with transport companies on this, it will be a success, Glading said in a statement.
We're getting really tired of looking like the Watchers.
However, surfing the Internet, sending e-mails and text messages, or downloading data will continue to be banned below 2 miles (3 kilometers) above sea level, the agency said.
Passengers will be advised to switch their smartphones, tablets and other devices to airplane mode.
So still no Words with Friends, the online game of Scrabble that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011 when he was famously kicked off an American Airlines plane for refusing to turn off his device while the plane was parked at the gate.
And heavier devices like laptops will have to be kept in storage for fear of injuring someone if they fly over the cabin.
Cell phone calls will continue to be prohibited on board.
The rules for using cell phones are not set by the FAA, they're set by the Federal Communications Commission.
The FAA may lift the ban on certain electronic devices during take-off and landing.
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a national transportation safety expert for CBS News, said that cell phones are still considered a risk.
"Mobile phones are a real problem, not only because they can potentially create interference with navigation devices, but we also know from FCC data that they can cause interference with broadcast towers in the air", Rosenker said.
A professional advisory committee set up by the FAA to investigate the issue last month proposed that the government allow the widespread use of electronic devices.
The FAA has been under pressure in recent years to ease restrictions on their use.
Critics such as Senator Claire McCaskill, a Democrat from Missouri, argue that there is no legitimate security reason for the ban.
Restrictions are also becoming increasingly difficult to enforce because of the widespread use of such devices.
Some studies suggest that as many as one third of passengers forget or ignore the obligation to turn off their devices.
The FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices by passengers in 1966 in response to disruptions to navigation and communications equipment when passengers began carrying FM radios, a technical achievement of the time.
The new airlines rely on electrical systems far more than the previous generation of aircraft, but they are also designed, and approved by the FAA, to be resistant to electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering passengers the use of Wi-Fi at travel altitudes for several years.
Plans tailored for Wi-Fi systems are also more resistant to interference.
The vast majority of airlines should adapt to the increased use of electronic devices under the new rules, Huert said.
Modern electronic devices generally emit much less intense radio emissions than previous generations.
For example, e-readers emit only minimal power when the page is turned.
But the transmission is stronger when the device downloads or transmits data.
The Commission has also examined whether the aid measure in question constitutes State aid within the meaning of Article 107 (1) TFEU.
In 2011, the company's representatives loaded a commercial airliner with their Kindle e-readers and conducted a test flight, but no problems emerged.
The Commission has not received any comments from interested parties.
Douglas Kidd of the National Airline Passenger Association said he believes that interference from these devices is real, even when the risk is minimal.
Other members of the committee stated that there are only fragmentary reports from pilots to support the fact that such devices can cause interference with aircraft systems, and most of these reports are very old.
However, the Committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to order passengers to turn off their instruments during flight in low visibility.
The tourism industry group welcomed the changes and considered them to be a sensible course for the traveling public, which makes extensive use of technology.
"We are pleased that the FAA has recognized that a pleasant travel experience does not compromise safety", said Roger Dow, executive director of the American Travel Association.
