Is the European elite ready to trade with Britain?
The Business for Britain campaign was launched in April with the promise to bring businesses together and define the changes British business and job-creating companies want to see in their relationship with the EU.
To this end, we commissioned the largest and most comprehensive survey to ask the UK's leading businesspeople what they think of Britain, trade and the EU.
YouGov surveyed 1,000 business leaders representing UK businesses of all sizes and from different sectors and regions.
The results of the survey will surprise many.
We found that the vast majority of companies are now trying to export outside Europe and are concentrating on countries that are modernising and growing while EU countries are stagnating.
They want to see the government prioritize new trade links with countries like China, India and Brazil rather than get bogged down in a long and arduous process of reforming secretive European institutions.
When asked for their views on specific policy areas  from monopoly regulation to product laws, most businesspeople expressed the view that control of these key competences should be returned to Westminster.
There was general dissatisfaction with the single market and businessmen said that the costs of Brussels regulations now outweighed the benefits of being part of the European trading area  Even 40 percent of large companies, traditionally the most pro-European companies, agreed.
And finally, our survey of business leaders revealed the most telling insight, which is that a clear majority want Britain to seek a change in the treaty and relationship with the EU that should be based on trade, not politics.
The finding, which was shared by businesses of all sizes and major business groups, shows that the business sector is pushing for a 'meaningful change' that will bring the influence back to Britain.
The stakes are high  getting a treaty change and a better deal for Britain could mean a gain of up to 16% in the referendum vote on remaining in the EU.
The Prime Minister should not hesitate: this survey shows that British business supports his plan to revise the terms of Britain's EU membership.
This also shows that the business sector expects this amendment to represent a significant shift from the current balance of power back towards the UK.
A better deal for Britain is possible and even more necessary as the euro area embarks on a path towards closer economic and fiscal union.
The priority must be jobs and growth in Britain, and as our survey results show, for business this means a refocus on trade and a fundamental change in Brussels' regulatory approach.
