Scientists shed more light on how tail movements affect a dog's mood
Previous research has shown that happy dogs wag their tails more to the right (from a dog's point of view), while nervous dogs wag their tails more to the left.
Now, however, scientists say that other dogs can sense and respond to these subtle differences in tail movements.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neurobiologist at the University of Trent, said: "It is well known that the left and right sides of the brain have different responses to stimuli that trigger positive or negative emotions".
We've been trying to find the same thing in other species.
He added that, as in humans, the right side of the brain is responsible for left-handedness and vice versa, and that these two hemispheres play different roles in emotion.
To learn more about how dogs respond to the disproportionate wagging of other dogs' tails, researchers monitored animals watching other dogs' movies.
They measured the heart rate of these animals and analyzed their behavior.
It probably won't take long to understand why their tails go one way and the other.
Professor Vallortigara said: "We have shown dogs films about dogs, either in the natural version or in silhouette, to remove any confusing stimuli, and we have also been able to adjust the tail movement to show it more to the right or left".
When the animals saw the otherwise inconspicuous dog wagging its tail to the right (from the dog's point of view wagging its tail), they remained completely calm.
But when she noticed the tail turning mostly to the left (again from the dog's tail wagging view), their heart rate increased and the animals seemed insecure.
Professor Vallortigara said he didn't think dogs would consciously communicate with each other through these movements.
Rather, he believes that dogs have learned from experience which movements they must and must not watch.
He said, "If you meet a dog several times and the tail movements in one direction are repeatedly associated with more friendly behavior and the movement to the right produces less friendly behavior, you will respond based on that experience".
Researchers say the findings can help dog owners, veterinarians, and trainers better understand their pets' emotions.
Dog behavior expert John Bradshaw, a veterinary professor at the University of Bristol, said that this was not the first study to examine whether the left and right sides of dogs are important.
Last year, a team at Lincoln University found that dogs turn their heads to the left when they look at an aggressive dog, and to the right when they look at a cheerful dog.
And in another paper from the University of Victoria in Canada, he said, "Dogs were more likely to be introduced to a robot dog when it wagged its tail left than right, when it became more insecure -- the exact opposite of the Italian study".
He said the difference may be that dogs in these different studies of the animals in the movies or the dog robots didn't behave quite like dogs.
He explained that a study of how dogs react to real dogs might help.
Although there is strong evidence that in many different mammals, both sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be clarified  and dogs are no exception, he said.
But because of how easy it is to observe their behavior, it may not take long to understand why their tails sometimes turn to one side and sometimes to the other.
