In a statement announcing the news, Father Federico Lombardi, a Vatican spokesman, said that a meeting of current cardinals, known as a consistory, would precede the solemn elevation of new cardinals.
"Pope Francis has decided to announce his decision to convene the February Consistory in advance to facilitate planning for other gatherings that require the participation of cardinals from different parts of the world", Lombardi said.
Jack Valero of Catholic Voices said the number of cardinal electors is likely to fall by February.
He said that the pope usually appoints as many cardinals as are needed to increase the number of voters back to 120, and as many cardinals over 80 as he wants.
The Consistory next year will be significant because it will be the first since Francis was elected in March of this year, Valero said.
At the moment, there is a certain orientation towards Europe.
"It will be interesting to see if the new pope nominates cardinals from the rest of the world to restore balance", he said.
Forty percent of Roman Catholics are in South America, but they have only a small number of cardinals.
It will also be the first election of cardinals since Francis established the Council of Cardinals, a group of eight cardinals from around the world tasked with finding ways to reform the church.
