Nathaniel P. Morris is a second-year medical student at Harvard.
I'm reading a very sad book these days.
I thought this book would encourage me during the dark days of my second year in medical school and give me a glimmer of hope.
It's called The Audacity to Win, and it's a memoir of Barack Obama's 2008 presidential campaign.
When I finish my patient reviews at night and go to bed, the book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions and speeches took your breath away.
The election ended in a landslide, and the television news made us reflect on the historical value of this moment.
My classmates were crying with joy, and my parents hid the newspapers they had obtained.
A young team of visionaries was heading to the White House, and the nation was ready for a change.
When he took office in 2008, Obama had an approval rating of 82 percent.
And this is where I close the book.
Going into the present is a rough wake-up call, like waking up from a dream.
It's hard to remember these optimistic days... they seem like distant memories, sad reminders of missed opportunities.
In the years since I cast my first ballot, things have really changed.
It was definitely not what I imagined.
I recognize that Obama has achieved a number of great and varied successes -- from the Affordable Care Act to the withdrawal of our troops from Iraq to ending the "don't ask, don't tell" policy after the killing of Osama bin Laden.
I also believe that partisan obstruction has thwarted so many efforts to move our nation forward: among others, immigration reform, public health care choice, and closing the base at Guantanamo.
But after many occasions of defending the Obama administration in front of my colleagues and friends, I've reached the absolute limit of what they can offer.
I found myself in a place of political hopelessness.
Republican obstructionism cannot explain the authorization of wiretapping foreign leaders or drone strikes that kill innocent children overseas.
They don't explain why the NSA collects data on the private lives of Americans, or why it goes after those who expose government malpractice.
They cannot be held responsible for the execution of Anwar al-Awlaki, an American citizen, without due process of law, or for curbing public contributions and spending during presidential campaigns.
They cannot justify the report's finding that the White House's efforts to silence the media are "more aggressive... than the Nixon administration".
And most recently, they can't even excuse their failure to create a simple website more than three years after the Affordable Care Act was signed.
I don't know if I could have expected anything like this.
Did I realize at 18 that government power could conflict with the political campaigns that preceded it?
Elected office obviously has no predictable course, and our public conversations will be shaped by the opposition political party and random events like the massacre in Newton.
However, all the examples I have given above seem to be largely the result of the administration's own decision.
And that's what bothers me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, but not because I was excited about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney presented a confused and unpolished alternative and seemed unable to consolidate his policies or position.
I felt that a second term for Obama, free from the pressure of the next election, would fulfill the hopes we'd heard about before.
Yet going back to 2008  with Obama's support falling below 45% this week  through this book is getting harder.
It makes me remember all the promises that have been broken.
I read a chapter in a book this week about how Obama suffered a crushing defeat to Clinton in the Pennsylvania primary.
At an additional meeting during the campaign, he told his staff that he needed to get back on track and stay true to his mission.
"I want our spell back", he said.
We must not forget who we are.
It's been five years, Mr. President, and I completely agree with you.
The views expressed in this commentary are those of Nathaniel Morris.
