At least six authorities worldwide  the European Commission, Finma, the Swiss Antimonopoly Authority Weko, the FCA, the US Department of Justice and the Hong Kong Monetary Authority  are investigating allegations that these bankers conspired to manipulate the currency market.
People familiar with the situation said that HSBC, Citigroup, JPMorgan and Credit Suisse have also launched internal investigations or received requests for information from the relevant authorities.
Banks are sifting through years of old instant messages and emails to find any cases of wrongdoing.
Reports of the investigations have alarmed traders in an area that has been one of the biggest engines for generating profit in investment bank closings in recent years, but which has been disrupted by the small currency volatility limiting opportunities for speculators.
Some bankers have tried to downplay the seriousness of the situation by claiming that with a large and highly liquid foreign exchange market, it is essentially impossible to manipulate, but senior traders say that may not necessarily be true.
