Of the 61 percent of companies that are actively engaged in the new codes, 26 percent said that their companies have already taken all necessary measures to be prepared in time.
Furthermore, 35 per cent of these companies are planning to take the necessary measures in the near future.
In contrast, one in five companies has not yet dealt with recoding, yet they have a concrete idea of how to prepare for it.
A total of 11 percent have no opinion and cannot judge the issue.
Only 8% of companies admit that they have not yet addressed the issues related to recoding.
The most important legal topic related to the new Civil Code is the conclusion of new contracts (21%) for the largest number of companies surveyed, followed by the settlement of business terms (16%) and changes in the land register and liability for damage (ten per cent each).
The Treaty of Lisbon is the most important new development in the whole process of recodification, unifying the treaty law only in the new Civil Code.
The current parallel regulation in the Civil and Commercial Code will be abolished, which should make contract law more transparent for citizens and businesses.
