He travels through mud, river and jungle, providing free medical care
Dr. Georges Bwelle provides free medical care in the villages of Cameroon.
Bwelle and his team treat hundreds of patients almost every weekend
In West African countries, there are not many doctors; only one for every 5,000 people.
Vote here or on your mobile phone.
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of the top 10 contenders for the 2013 CNN Hero Award.
In the 2013 CNN Hero Award competition, you can vote for him or any of the top ten nominees.
The winner will receive $250,000 to continue their extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched his father fall unconscious over and over again and drive to hospitals that were not equipped to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident near the Cameroon capital of Yaoundé in 1981.
At first, he was treated with only a broken arm, but then he developed an infection that spread to his brain, where it formed a hematoma that would plague him for the rest of his life.
"There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon", says Georges Bwelle.
We'd have to take him out of Cameroon if we had the money.
Instead, Bwelle spent years transporting his father to overcrowded clinics and hospitals, where he received the treatment that was simply available.
"It's not easy", says Bwelle.
You can leave your house at 5 a.m., rush to the hospital to be there first, but you're not the first.
There's a lot of patients.
Some people die just because they have to wait.
Since Bwelle's father died in 2002, the situation has not changed much.
According to the World Health Organization, there is only one doctor for every 5,000 people in Cameroon.
Just for comparison, the United States has one doctor for every 413 people.
And even if Cameroonians could visit doctors, many would not be able to afford it.
Two out of five people in that country live below the poverty line, and nearly three-quarters of health care spending in that country is private.
"The only problem they have is poverty", says Bwelle.
They can't enjoy life because of poverty.
After seeing his father and many of his countrymen suffer, Bwelle decided to do something about it.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers performed 700 free surgeries last year.
He became a vascular surgeon at the Central Hospital in Yaoundé.
And he started a nonprofit organization called ASCOVIME, whose members visit rural areas on weekends to provide free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 others stuff their vans, attach medical supplies to rooftops, and travel through rough terrain to villages in need of help.
They're not always happy.
More than once, vehicles have to push through river and mud.
But when they arrive, they are greeted as true heroes: feasting, singing and dancing, and the best accommodations the community can offer.
In these villages, free medical care is truly a cause for celebration, and Bwelle  with her broad smile and unbridled energy  is very willing to join in the local cheer.
The next day, the team starts treating hundreds of patients.
"We have 500 patients on each trip", says Bwelle.
They come to the village from a radius of 60 kilometers, and they walk.
During each of these weekends, doctors provide a variety of medical care.
Many are being treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasitic diseases, and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may receive crutches or donated glasses or a free birth certificate - a document that the school requires but that many impoverished families simply cannot afford.
At night, the team performs simple operations under local anesthesia.
The surgery is usually done in a school building, a town hall, or at home; after the operation, the patient gets up and goes to the recovery area to make room for another patient.
Using the light from a generator, an operating room, and hygienic equipment, Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of the morning.
It's exhausting, but village musicians usually help the team stay motivated.
"They play drums all night to keep us up and working", says Bwelle.
On Sunday, the team will head back to town, tired but proud of their work.
This group  made up of Cameroonian doctors and international medical students  performed 700 free operations last year and is aware that their help can mean a lot to the local population.
One man said that after hernia surgery, he would be able to work again.
"It will change the future of our family", said the man.
In addition to organizing these weekend clinics and working as a surgeon at Bwelle Hospital, he also works at night for private health clinics around Yaoundé.
He says that this latter work finances about 60% of his nonprofit activities; the rest is covered by private contributions.
"I'm not sure when she's actually sleeping", says Katie O'Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia who volunteers for Bwelle's group.
He's always either in the hospital or trying to raise money for the organization to run these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students like O'Malley who have come from the United States or Europe to join Bwelle on his mission, it's a great practice they couldn't get back home.
"We washed Dr. Bwell's hands thoroughly and removed blood stains or held his instruments", says O'Malley.
You'll never experience that as a second-year medical student in America.
Student volunteers usually pay their own way to Cameroon and often arrive with donated medical supplies.
But once they arrive in Yaoundé, Bwelle provides food, transportation, and education.
"He is without a doubt a hero", says O'Malley.
He gives his life to this organization and his desire to help the people of Cameroon is endless.
For Bwelle, the constant downpour is not a burden.
Helping others to live happier lives, fulfilling a promise he made to his Father, is something that brings him great joy.
"I'm so happy doing this job", says Bwelle.
And I think about my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
To make people laugh, to ease their pain... that's why I do it.
Take a look at the ASCOVIME website and find out how you can help.
